I've found some strange behavior when targeting netstandard2.0 and cost me at least 10 hours to find easy/strange fix.

foo.c:

    #include <stdio.h>
    void foo(void)
    {
      puts("Hello, I'm a shared library");
    }

run following commands in your bash 
     
     gcc -c -fpic foo.c
     gcc -shared -o libfoo.so foo.o

     
test.csproj

      <Project Sdk="Microsoft.NET.Sdk">
      
        <PropertyGroup>
          <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>
          <TargetFramework>netstandard2.0</TargetFramework>
        </PropertyGroup>
      </Project>        

Program.cs

      using System;
      using System.Runtime.InteropServices;
      
      namespace cs
      {
          class Program
          {
              [DllImport("foo")]
              private static extern void foo();
      
              static void Main(string[] args)
              {
                 foo();
                  Console.WriteLine("Hello World!");
              }
          }
      }

So now if you run it with TargetFramework as netcoreapp2.0. It will work.

If you run it with TargetFramework as netstandard2.0 you will get an exception on foo module not found.

      Unhandled Exception: System.DllNotFoundException: Unable to load DLL 'foo': The specified module could not be found. (Exception from HRESULT: 0x8007007E)
      at cs.Program.foo()
      at cs.Program.Main(String[] args) in /mnt/d/Projects/test/bugtest/cs/Program.cs:line 13

What I experienced in my bigger project was being compiled with netstandard2.0 with presense of foo.dll would generate "bad image format exception", and "no module found" with libfoo.so which is way more challenging as I was pointing the problem to my C++ code.

Anyway I know this is a console app so it should be netcoreapp2.0 but it is a common mistake that I do (and assume many others) which also end up in a binrary that runs anyway! (if it is a wrong target why compiler does not warn?!)

